  "prompt": "Why is it that entrepreneurship is not decreasing poverty in zimbabwe?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why entrepreneurship has not effectively reduced poverty in Zimbabwe:\n\n1. Economic Instability\n- Hyperinflation\n- Currency volatility\n- Frequent economic policy changes\n- High levels of economic uncertainty\n\n2. Limited Access to Capital\n- Lack of affordable financing\n- High interest rates\n- Limited banking infrastructure\n- Strict lending requirements\n\n3. Challenging Business Environment\n- Complex bureaucratic processes\n- Excessive regulatory requirements\n- High operational costs\n- Corruption\n- Weak legal protection for businesses\n\n4. Infrastructure Limitations\n- Poor transportation networks\n- Unreliable electricity supply\n- Limited technological infrastructure\n- Inadequate telecommunications\n\n5. Market Constraints\n- Small domestic market\n- Limited purchasing power\n- Reduced consumer spending\n- High import dependency\n\n6. Political Instability\n- Frequent political tensions\n- Inconsistent governance\n- Lack of investor confidence\n- Potential for sudden policy changes\n\n7. Skills and Education Gaps\n- Limited entrepreneurship training\n- Inadequate business management skills\n- Low technical and vocational education\n- Brain drain of skilled professionals\n\n8. External Economic Factors\n- International sanctions\n- Global economic fluctuations\n- Limited international trade opportunities\n\nThese interconnected challenges create significant barriers for entrepreneurs, preventing them from effectively generating sustainable economic growth and reducing poverty.",
